  "prompt": "Union Public Service Commission (India): Is the number of optionals are reduced to one(paper 1 nd paper 2) OR they are two only wid the difference of only one paper for each optionals?",
  "response": "The Union Public Service Commission (UPSC) conducts the Civil Services Examination (CSE) in India, which is a highly competitive exam for recruitment to various civil services of the Government of India, including the Indian Administrative Service (IAS), Indian Police Service (IPS), and Indian Foreign Service (IFS), among others.\n\nAs of the latest information available, the UPSC has not reduced the number of optional subjects to one. Candidates are still required to choose one optional subject, and for that optional subject, they will have to write two papers: **Paper I and Paper II**. Each paper is of **250 marks**, making the total marks for the optional subject **500 marks**.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Optional Subject Choice**: Candidates can choose **one** optional subject from the list provided by UPSC.\n2. **Papers for Optional Subject**: The chosen optional subject has **two papers** (Paper I and Paper II), each carrying 250 marks.\n3. **Total Marks**: The optional subject contributes **500 marks** to the total score in the Mains examination.\n\nThus, the optional subject remains a significant part of the UPSC Mains examination, and candidates must prepare thoroughly for both papers of their chosen optional subject. There is no change in the structure of having two papers for the optional subject.",
